#Attributes 
Used Attributes to control the behaviour of elements.
And also act as a modifier for HTML element types.

->HTML attributes provide extra information about HTML elements.
->Attributes names and values are case sensitive
->Attributes comprise of two parts a name and a value
They are always written inside the opening tag and usually come in name="value" pairs.

Basic syntax:
<tagname attribute="value">Content</tagname>

Example:
<p align="left">This is left aligned</p>
<p align="center">This is right aligned</p>
<p align="right">This is right aligned</p>


Common HTML Attributes with Examples
1. href (used in links)
Specifies the URL of a link.

<a href="https://www.google.com">Visit Google</a>

2. src (used in images, videos, etc.)
Specifies the path to the media file.

<img src="image.jpg" alt="A sample image">

3. alt (alternative text for images)
Provides text if the image cannot load.

<img src="cat.jpg" alt="Cute cat">

4. title
Shows extra information when you hover over the element.

<p title="This is a tooltip">Hover over this text</p>

5. style
Applies inline CSS styles.
<p style="color: blue;">This text is blue.</p>

6. id
Gives a unique identifier to an element.

<p id="intro">Welcome to my website</p>

7. class
Used to group elements for CSS or JavaScript.

<p class="highlight">Important text</p>

8. target (used in links)(_blank, _self, _parent)
Specifies where to open the link.

<a href="https://example.com" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a>

9.width and height in an Image
They define the display size of the image in pixels.

<img src="cat.jpg" width="200" height="150" alt="Cute cat">

example:
width="200" → image width is 200 pixels
height="150" → image height is 150 pixels